#Approach:
Merge Intervals – Sorting + Traversal Approach

Sabse pehle intervals ko starting time ke basis par sort karte hain.

Phir first interval ko answer me daal dete hain aur usse current merged interval maan lete hain.

Ab baaki intervals ko ek ek karke check karte hain:
Agar current merged interval ka end, next interval ke start se greater ya equal hai,
to dono overlap karte hain.
Is case me merged interval ka end update kar dete hain using max(end1, end2).

Agar overlap nahi hai, to iska matlab new disjoint interval start ho gaya hai.
To usse answer me add kar dete hain aur usse new current merged interval bana dete hain.

End me saare merged intervals return kar dete hain.

Time Complexity: O(n log n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

#Code:

import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int[][] merge(int[][] intervals) {
        if(intervals.length <= 1){
            return intervals;
        }

        Arrays.sort(intervals, Comparator.comparingInt(a -> a[0]));

        List<int[]> result = new ArrayList<>();
        int[] newInterval = intervals[0];
        result.add(newInterval);

        for(int[] interval : intervals){
            if(newInterval[1] >= interval[0]){
                newInterval[1] = Math.max(newInterval[1], interval[1]);
            }
            else{
                newInterval = interval;
                result.add(newInterval);
            }
        }

        return result.toArray(new int[result.size()][]);
    }
}
